1
00:00:29,816 --> 00:00:32,115
Boy, am I glad to see you guys.

2
00:00:32,546 --> 00:00:35,398
We are sorely ill-prepared
for this kind of deal.

3
00:00:37,305 --> 00:00:39,709
Quail hunter's dog found her
this morning at 5:30.

4
00:00:41,198 --> 00:00:43,383
Wasn't meant to be hunting quail,
but he was.

5
00:00:43,719 --> 00:00:45,005
Do we know who she is?

6
00:00:45,166 --> 00:00:47,676
Nope. Looks familiar, though,
so I'm guessing local.

7
00:00:50,705 --> 00:00:53,348
People sure look different
when they're dead, though, don't they?

8
00:00:57,217 --> 00:00:58,697
That wound doesn't look fatal.

9
00:01:00,883 --> 00:01:04,054
There's no ligature marks on the neck,
so she wasn't strangled or hung.

10
00:01:04,445 --> 00:01:06,806
Gums are livid.
Eyes are hemorrhaged.

11
00:01:07,313 --> 00:01:09,613
- Suffocation.
- My bet is

12
00:01:09,774 --> 00:01:12,297
it's a meth head from the city
coming in off the interstate.

13
00:01:12,635 --> 00:01:14,077
No, he's a local.

14
00:01:14,508 --> 00:01:17,580
And it was an accident. Her killer
didn't intend her to die this way.

15
00:01:17,740 --> 00:01:19,624
- How so?
- She still has her clothes on.

16
00:01:20,273 --> 00:01:23,016
Her abductor was taking her
to a location that was quiet and private

17
00:01:23,136 --> 00:01:25,190
so he could undress her
for a sexual assault.

18
00:01:25,527 --> 00:01:27,194
She made too much noise{\
at the wrong moment}.

19
00:01:27,314 --> 00:01:30,218
He tried to keep her quiet
and smothered her by mistake.

20
00:01:30,961 --> 00:01:32,961
No good to him now,
so then he dumps her

21
00:01:33,172 --> 00:01:34,224
in a spot

22
00:01:35,048 --> 00:01:36,432
only a local would know.

23
00:01:38,213 --> 00:01:40,013
She's all yours. Thanks for waiting.

24
00:01:49,895 --> 00:01:52,321
Why sexual motive?
Could be gangs or drugs.

25
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:55,326
- A drug trade smothering?
- By who... "Sesame street" crips?

26
00:01:55,998 --> 00:01:58,121
{\There's n}Nothing to say
it isn't just boyfriend trouble.

27
00:01:58,394 --> 00:01:59,812
Could be boyfriend trouble.

28
00:01:59,961 --> 00:02:01,411
Doesn't feel like it, though.

29
00:02:02,025 --> 00:02:03,128
Who is this guy?

30
00:02:03,838 --> 00:02:06,288
He's a consultant.
You want CBI assistance?

31
00:02:06,456 --> 00:02:07,881
He comes as part of the package.

32
00:02:08,463 --> 00:02:09,799
Consultant, huh?

33
00:02:10,336 --> 00:02:12,215
What, are you clairvoyant or some gizmo?

34
00:02:12,335 --> 00:02:13,928
You got psychic powers?

35
00:02:15,922 --> 00:02:16,925
No powers.

36
00:02:17,455 --> 00:02:19,851
Had them once. I mean,
I pretended I had them, obviously.

37
00:02:20,899 --> 00:02:24,372
- No such thing as psychic powers.
- So what is it you do, exactly?

38
00:02:26,962 --> 00:02:28,412
You know rock paper scissors?

39
00:02:28,865 --> 00:02:30,862
- I do.
- Play me.

40
00:02:32,107 --> 00:02:33,123
On three.

41
00:02:33,463 --> 00:02:35,033
One...
Two...

42
00:02:35,865 --> 00:02:36,865
Three.

43
00:03:03,972 --> 00:03:06,221
<i>Sync: Kasius</i>

44
00:03:22,211 --> 00:03:23,390
Go inside the house.

45
00:03:24,185 --> 00:03:26,292
Go do your homework.
Get your homework started.

46
00:03:26,521 --> 00:03:27,688
Go. Go now.

47
00:03:31,523 --> 00:03:32,523
Joe?

48
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:58,074
Mr. And Mrs. O'Keefe?
I'm agent Teresa Lisbon,

49
00:03:58,460 --> 00:04:00,332
California Bureau of Investigation.

50
00:04:01,459 --> 00:04:03,203
I'm sorry. We're bringing bad news.

51
00:04:04,782 --> 00:04:06,314
We found your daughter Melanie.

52
00:04:47,084 --> 00:04:48,084
Who are you?

53
00:04:49,447 --> 00:04:51,085
{\My name's }Patrick Jane.
I'm with the police.

54
00:04:53,317 --> 00:04:54,752
Is this your sister's room?

55
00:05:03,441 --> 00:05:04,872
Did someone kill my sister?

56
00:05:15,020 --> 00:05:17,737
She didn't come home from work
the night before last.

57
00:05:18,245 --> 00:05:20,657
She waitresses
at the Shand Creek winery restaurant.

58
00:05:21,432 --> 00:05:23,284
She was on until 11:00.

59
00:05:23,806 --> 00:05:25,256
Her car is still parked there

60
00:05:25,932 --> 00:05:28,004
- in the parking lot.
- We're always asleep

61
00:05:28,124 --> 00:05:30,563
when she comes home.
We didn't even know she was missing

62
00:05:30,683 --> 00:05:32,669
until the morning.
{\We c}Called all her friends,

63
00:05:33,149 --> 00:05:34,671
and nobody knew where she was.

64
00:05:34,881 --> 00:05:37,006
Nobody'd seen her
after she left work that night.

65
00:05:37,345 --> 00:05:39,550
She was all set to go to college
in the fall.

66
00:05:40,009 --> 00:05:42,006
She won a softball scholarship

67
00:05:43,214 --> 00:05:45,436
- at UCLA.
- We were worried about her

68
00:05:45,556 --> 00:05:47,934
going down to L.A.
because you read about all the crime.

69
00:05:52,434 --> 00:05:53,856
Did they do anything to her?

70
00:05:55,243 --> 00:05:56,435
Doesn't appear so.

71
00:05:57,182 --> 00:05:58,486
She was fully clothed.

72
00:06:00,058 --> 00:06:02,108
Why would anybody
do something like that?

73
00:06:02,810 --> 00:06:05,532
Oftentimes, the first name that pops
into the mother's head

74
00:06:05,652 --> 00:06:06,866
is the guilty party.

75
00:06:07,655 --> 00:06:09,747
Jealous boyfriends, anything like that?

76
00:06:12,028 --> 00:06:13,960
- Nothing like that.
- Nothing?

77
00:06:14,614 --> 00:06:16,176
She was always shy of boys.

78
00:06:17,181 --> 00:06:18,640
She was a good girl.

79
00:06:19,492 --> 00:06:23,011
She took the purity pledge
in ninth grade,

80
00:06:24,620 --> 00:06:26,707
and she still wears that ring today.

81
00:06:45,183 --> 00:06:47,012
When did she take the posters down?

82
00:06:47,737 --> 00:06:50,246
- After Christmas.
- Who was on the posters?

83
00:06:51,119 --> 00:06:53,166
Boys with long hair from the TV.

84
00:06:55,118 --> 00:06:57,920
- She didn't like them anymore?
- Said they were for little girls.

85
00:07:01,188 --> 00:07:02,467
{\Do y}You know who killed her?

86
00:07:35,904 --> 00:07:39,629
- Are you gonna find out who killed her?
- Me and my colleagues are gonna try.

87
00:07:40,017 --> 00:07:40,838
How?

88
00:07:41,951 --> 00:07:44,467
Looking, listening, asking questions.

89
00:07:45,362 --> 00:07:47,053
When you find him, will you tell me?

90
00:07:47,719 --> 00:07:48,913
Sure. Why?

91
00:07:51,822 --> 00:07:52,892
No reason.

92
00:08:05,179 --> 00:08:06,405
- Rigsby.
- Van Pelt.

93
00:08:06,565 --> 00:08:08,819
{\Did y}You get the fax
from the sheriff's department there?

94
00:08:09,300 --> 00:08:12,043
<i>Run the details through the crime
database, see if we get any matches.</i>

95
00:08:12,163 --> 00:08:13,754
- Okay, Van Pelt?
- Will do.

96
00:08:13,874 --> 00:08:16,011
I finished the budget reports here
like you said.

97
00:08:16,243 --> 00:08:18,668
- Why don't I drive down there?{\give you guys a hand?}
- No, you stay there.

98
00:08:19,007 --> 00:08:21,633
- Look, I'll call you if I need you.
- She has a lover...

99
00:08:22,198 --> 00:08:24,507
Someone she met
around Christmas at a fair.

100
00:08:25,262 --> 00:08:27,329
He's either too old, too closely related

101
00:08:27,449 --> 00:08:30,449
or too villainous to tell her folks
about. I'd bet on villainy.

102
00:08:30,798 --> 00:08:32,473
His first name starts with an "H".

103
00:08:32,633 --> 00:08:34,853
Explains why she wasn't wearing
a purity ring.

104
00:08:35,220 --> 00:08:38,373
You know, it is the damndest thing.
I was at the Shand Creek that night

105
00:08:38,493 --> 00:08:41,297
on a call round about the same time
that girl was taken.

106
00:08:41,839 --> 00:08:43,430
A drunk wouldn't pay his check.

107
00:08:43,765 --> 00:08:47,238
That is the damndest thing. You notice
anything that might be useful?

108
00:08:49,322 --> 00:08:50,700
For crying out loud.

109
00:08:52,006 --> 00:08:53,480
When I got there,

110
00:08:53,728 --> 00:08:56,913
I saw a black truck, full-size, taking
off out of the other end of that lot

111
00:08:57,075 --> 00:08:58,667
going way too fast...

112
00:09:04,585 --> 00:09:06,337
Nearly went after him, too, you know?

113
00:09:07,867 --> 00:09:09,168
What time was that?

114
00:09:10,244 --> 00:09:11,527
A quarter to 12:00.

115
00:09:13,215 --> 00:09:14,764
Have these woods been checked?

116
00:09:15,580 --> 00:09:16,601
Not to speak of.

117
00:09:16,906 --> 00:09:19,020
You might want to put
a few man-hours into that.

118
00:09:23,571 --> 00:09:25,321
That's her car right there.

119
00:09:26,190 --> 00:09:27,549
You want to take it?

120
00:09:29,108 --> 00:09:31,851
She worked for us for...
three summers in a row.

121
00:09:32,822 --> 00:09:33,822
Lovely girl.

122
00:09:35,141 --> 00:09:36,257
This is good.

123
00:09:36,739 --> 00:09:38,414
- Yes, it is.
- It's unbelievable.

124
00:09:38,948 --> 00:09:41,853
And from the parking lot.
I was practically right there.

125
00:09:42,322 --> 00:09:44,049
I can't even think about it. Mm-hmm.

126
00:09:45,382 --> 00:09:46,382
Try this.

127
00:09:47,220 --> 00:09:48,236
No, I won't.

128
00:09:48,356 --> 00:09:50,391
- This one's really good.
- To your knowledge,

129
00:09:50,511 --> 00:09:53,888
did Melanie ever have any incidents
with disgruntled coworkers, maybe...

130
00:09:54,131 --> 00:09:55,336
Boyfriend problems?

131
00:09:56,675 --> 00:09:59,250
This one is really good. Cardamom?

132
00:09:59,531 --> 00:10:00,853
Yes, and caraway.

133
00:10:01,696 --> 00:10:02,913
And a lot of butter.

134
00:10:04,225 --> 00:10:06,150
There's no shame in it.
A lot of butter.

135
00:10:06,818 --> 00:10:09,695
T{\hat's t}he great thing about food.
Indulgence and necessity all in one.

136
00:10:10,097 --> 00:10:12,142
What time did Melanie leave work
that night?

137
00:10:12,262 --> 00:10:14,368
To build a time line,
we need to know exactly.

138
00:10:14,488 --> 00:10:17,578
I know she took off first, But I'd have
to check her time card to be exact.

139
00:10:19,740 --> 00:10:21,165
It wasn't me, by the way.

140
00:10:21,326 --> 00:10:24,252
I have a staff of 20 who'll tell you
the only time I ever leave the kitchen

141
00:10:24,372 --> 00:10:26,180
is to take a leak or yell at a customer.

142
00:10:26,876 --> 00:10:28,256
Sad but true.

143
00:10:29,765 --> 00:10:31,260
So this is the kitchen.

144
00:10:31,380 --> 00:10:34,595
This is the main prep area,
and this is where the magic happens.

145
00:10:36,953 --> 00:10:39,183
Attention, Randall! Pay it!

146
00:10:39,343 --> 00:10:40,672
My office is this way.

147
00:10:41,668 --> 00:10:42,895
This is a go.

148
00:10:47,158 --> 00:10:49,576
She was by no means a gifted server.

149
00:10:49,696 --> 00:10:52,228
"Betty butterfingers",
that's what we called her,

150
00:10:52,720 --> 00:10:54,365
but she had a good spirit.

151
00:10:57,654 --> 00:10:59,370
She left at 11:25.

152
00:11:06,134 --> 00:11:08,115
- Good night.
- She went out that door

153
00:11:09,499 --> 00:11:11,054
and that's the last we saw of her.

154
00:11:13,005 --> 00:11:14,688
It's all reservations, I assume?

155
00:11:15,380 --> 00:11:17,752
- Credit cards?
- Yes. I can get you a full list.

156
00:11:17,872 --> 00:11:19,492
- Great.
- Raquel, come in.

157
00:11:20,180 --> 00:11:23,012
These people are here to help find out
what happened to poor Melanie.

158
00:11:24,813 --> 00:11:26,069
Okay. Good.

159
00:11:29,752 --> 00:11:31,735
You and she were good friends,
weren't you?

160
00:11:32,437 --> 00:11:34,363
Not really. She was okay.

161
00:11:36,877 --> 00:11:39,759
Cause on her wall at home, she has
a picture of you and her together.

162
00:11:42,710 --> 00:11:44,526
That's weird, huh?

163
00:11:45,641 --> 00:11:48,067
I don't know why she has
a picture of me and her, ma'am.

164
00:11:48,187 --> 00:11:50,373
Maybe she has a secret crush on me.
I don't know.

165
00:11:50,493 --> 00:11:53,167
- What's her boyfriend's name?
- She doesn't have a boyfriend.

166
00:11:53,650 --> 00:11:56,533
That's her thing, right?
Purity. No boys.

167
00:11:56,963 --> 00:11:58,862
So who was it that she cut out
of the picture?

168
00:11:58,982 --> 00:12:00,639
- I don't know.
- You were there.

169
00:12:00,957 --> 00:12:03,243
It was Christmas. I was high.

170
00:12:05,064 --> 00:12:07,214
Raquel, this is a murder investigation.

171
00:12:07,616 --> 00:12:10,399
If you protect someone who did this,
you'll do time.

172
00:12:11,313 --> 00:12:13,013
I'm sorry, ma'am. I can't help you.

173
00:12:13,355 --> 00:12:15,613
I would if I could. Swear to God.

174
00:12:16,572 --> 00:12:17,490
Thank you.

175
00:12:21,936 --> 00:12:22,936
Car's clean.

176
00:12:23,079 --> 00:12:26,585
Have a chat with Raquel, why don't you?
Gonna go check the credit card receipts.

177
00:12:28,869 --> 00:12:31,712
Give me a minute with her.
She's got a super low threshold.

178
00:12:31,872 --> 00:12:32,755
Nope.

179
00:12:32,915 --> 00:12:35,424
Just stand in the doorway,
pretend you're making a phone call{\ for a moment}.

180
00:12:35,734 --> 00:12:37,802
It's illegal and it's unprofessional.

181
00:12:37,962 --> 00:12:40,137
That's why I need you
to stand in the doorway.

182
00:12:41,413 --> 00:12:42,417
One minute.

183
00:12:50,588 --> 00:12:51,819
Raquel, look at me.

184
00:12:52,893 --> 00:12:55,740
Before you fall asleep tonight,
while you're lying in your bed relaxing

185
00:12:55,860 --> 00:12:57,692
and slowly drifting off into sleep,

186
00:12:58,558 --> 00:12:59,929
I want you to think of me.

187
00:13:00,348 --> 00:13:02,335
Think of me
and imagine that you can fly.

188
00:13:02,455 --> 00:13:05,954
Imagine you're weightless. You can float
gently into the air if you want to,

189
00:13:06,575 --> 00:13:09,534
safe and calm and serene.

190
00:13:09,880 --> 00:13:13,627
You can fly away, leave all your burdens
and worries and fears behind you.

191
00:13:15,891 --> 00:13:17,294
Imagine that...

192
00:13:17,644 --> 00:13:19,245
What a nice feeling it is.

193
00:13:20,552 --> 00:13:23,514
Next time you see me, when I say hello,
you'll remember that good feeling,

194
00:13:23,675 --> 00:13:26,411
you'll want to tell me the truth,
'cause when you do tell the truth,

195
00:13:26,531 --> 00:13:29,296
you'll feel that a heavy weight
has been lifted from your shoulders.

196
00:13:29,559 --> 00:13:32,407
I'll say hello,
and you will feel as light as a feather,

197
00:13:32,784 --> 00:13:34,600
as if you were floating on air.

198
00:13:35,841 --> 00:13:38,904
Why don't you sit here a moment, think
about that before you go back to work?

199
00:13:41,238 --> 00:13:42,266
Whatever.

200
00:13:43,421 --> 00:13:46,036
Your friend's crazy. Can I go now?

201
00:13:54,026 --> 00:13:55,337
Worked on the chicken.

202
00:13:56,536 --> 00:13:57,536
Right.

203
00:14:01,588 --> 00:14:02,720
Maybe that's a clue.

204
00:14:03,264 --> 00:14:04,264
"Sorry"?

205
00:14:12,078 --> 00:14:14,337
- Take it to the lab.
- I got a better idea.

206
00:14:16,016 --> 00:14:17,770
Settle down now, everyone.

207
00:14:17,890 --> 00:14:20,529
These are agents of
the California Bureau of Investigation.

208
00:14:21,141 --> 00:14:23,616
- They wanna talk to you a moment.
- {\There's n}Nothing to worry about.

209
00:14:26,986 --> 00:14:28,319
We need your help.

210
00:14:28,800 --> 00:14:29,872
Will you help us?

211
00:14:31,691 --> 00:14:33,814
We know the identity
of Melanie's killer.

212
00:14:34,263 --> 00:14:36,613
The murderer of that poor girl
is in this room.

213
00:14:40,848 --> 00:14:41,888
This note...

214
00:14:42,580 --> 00:14:44,303
was found in Melanie's locker.

215
00:14:45,516 --> 00:14:48,946
We have strong reason to believe
that whoever wrote this note

216
00:14:49,767 --> 00:14:50,809
is the killer.

217
00:14:52,608 --> 00:14:56,548
Unluckily for that person,
my colleague, agent Cho here,

218
00:14:56,668 --> 00:14:58,609
is the bureau's chief graphologist.

219
00:15:00,104 --> 00:15:03,044
Each one of you will be giving us
a sample of your handwriting,

220
00:15:03,164 --> 00:15:04,782
left and right-handed.

221
00:15:06,212 --> 00:15:09,827
Cho will examine these samples and
determine which of you left this note.

222
00:15:10,142 --> 00:15:11,580
Which of you is the killer?

223
00:15:17,337 --> 00:15:18,337
Randall?

224
00:15:19,045 --> 00:15:20,315
Back it up.

225
00:15:22,584 --> 00:15:23,587
<i>Voilà.</i>

226
00:15:30,008 --> 00:15:32,309
Randall, why did you want to say
"sorry" to Melanie?

227
00:15:33,387 --> 00:15:35,396
- Didn't kill her.
- Didn't say that you did.

228
00:15:35,900 --> 00:15:38,315
I asked why you wanted to say
"sorry" to her.

229
00:15:39,173 --> 00:15:42,132
Your time card and your boss say you
left work ten minutes before Melanie.

230
00:15:42,855 --> 00:15:44,738
You waited for her in the parking lot.

231
00:15:45,739 --> 00:15:46,739
Right?

232
00:15:48,326 --> 00:15:50,286
There's no law
against waiting for someone.{\ You waited for her.}

233
00:15:50,446 --> 00:15:52,955
- I just wanted to speak to her.
- Nothing wrong with that.

234
00:15:54,533 --> 00:15:56,625
You wanted to speak to her.
Then what happened?

235
00:15:59,279 --> 00:16:01,252
I was like,
"Hey, Melanie, what's up?"

236
00:16:02,207 --> 00:16:03,396
And we talked.

237
00:16:03,748 --> 00:16:04,852
She didn't leave.

238
00:16:05,335 --> 00:16:07,427
She was smiling and laughing,

239
00:16:07,753 --> 00:16:10,449
so I figured I was doing pretty good.
So...

240
00:16:10,799 --> 00:16:12,515
I made my move, and...

241
00:16:13,176 --> 00:16:15,268
she wasn't so into it,
which was cool,

242
00:16:15,602 --> 00:16:18,472
only I know she has
this whole virgin thing happening.

243
00:16:18,592 --> 00:16:21,025
So I figured
that I just have to be more...

244
00:16:21,782 --> 00:16:22,776
goal-oriented.

245
00:16:23,653 --> 00:16:25,447
She was pretty upset,

246
00:16:25,803 --> 00:16:29,079
She was pretty upset, so I apologized
for any misunderstanding, and I left.

